description:
File: lichen/subsys/lichen/link/schnorr48.c
Lines: 209-248

The stub schnorr48_stub_abort() function calls abort(), but the stub functions have return statements after the abort call:

```c
static void schnorr48_stub_abort(const char *func)
{
    LOG_WRN("FATAL: %s called without Monocypher - aborting\n", func);
    abort();
}

int schnorr48_sign(...)
{
    (void)privkey;
    // ...
    schnorr48_stub_abort("schnorr48_sign");
    return -1; /* unreachable, but satisfies compiler */
}
```

While the code is correct (abort() never returns), some static analyzers and compilers may not know abort() is noreturn, leading to:
1. Warnings about code after noreturn functions
2. If abort() is stubbed out in testing, the function returns -1 with uninitialized sig buffer

Impact: Low - abort() is standard noreturn. However, defensive coding would use __attribute__((noreturn)) or _Noreturn on the stub function.

Fix: Mark schnorr48_stub_abort with noreturn attribute:
```c
#if defined(__GNUC__) || defined(__clang__)
__attribute__((noreturn))
#endif
static void schnorr48_stub_abort(const char *func)
```
